export const BOOK = {
  meta: {
    title: "It's Always Her",
    subtitle: 'A ten-year letter to the girl who walked in through a quiet door.',
    author: 'Kranthi Kiran',
    place: 'Vizag · by the Bay of Bengal',
    dedication: [
      'For V — born on the twenty-fifth of December;',
      'and for the boy at the last bench',
      'who never learned to look away.',
    ],
  },
  chapters: [
    {
      id: 'prologue',
      kind: 'prologue',
      label: 'Prologue',
      title: 'It\u2019s Always Her',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `I am twenty-six now, and it is the middle of a December night, and the sea is doing the thing the sea does when it thinks no one is listening — breathing, slow and enormous, against the dark edge of the city I have never managed to leave.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `On my desk there is a small brass lamp. It is nothing special. I bought it years ago from a man on the beach road who sold puja things off a bicycle, and every year, on one particular date, I fill it with oil and light it and let it burn down to nothing while the rest of Vizag sleeps. I have never told anyone why. If you asked me — if you sat across from me in the yellow light and asked, plainly, _who is that lamp for?_ — I think I would finally have to say her name out loud, and I am not sure the room could hold it.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I have loved since then. I want that on the record, because this is not the story of a boy who sat frozen for a decade like a photograph nobody developed. I have loved, and lost, and been left, and done the leaving. I have typed goodnights to girls whose names I can no longer spell without a small pause of guilt. I have laughed, truly laughed, with women who became my friends, and I have told myself, on good mornings, with coffee going cold in my hand — _see. You have moved on. You are a whole person now._` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And then, some ordinary evening, the light will fall a certain way through a bus window. Or a stranger will tuck her hair behind her ear with two fingers, exactly two, the way only one person in the history of the world has ever done it. Or the calendar will simply turn, the way calendars do, indifferent and merciless, toward the twenty-fifth.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I close my eyes.` },
        { type: 'em', text: `And it is always her.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Ten years. Two colleges, three cities, one ocean, a hundred silences long enough to build a life inside. And still — this is the part I cannot explain to the people who love me and worry about me — when my heart is taken by the collar and asked, without ceremony, _whom do you belong to?_, it does not even pause to check its records. It does not consider the women who were kind to me, or the one who is being suggested to me now over careful dinners by careful relatives. It answers the way water answers gravity.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `This is the whole of it, then. A love that never became a relationship. A story with no scandal, no betrayal, no dramatic rain-soaked airport. Just a boy at a last bench, a girl at a half-open door, a breeze that came at exactly the wrong or exactly the right moment, and a lamp that has been lit ten Decembers running for someone who does not know it burns.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I have decided, finally, to write it down. Not to send. Not to confess. Only because a thing this long deserves, at least once, to be _said_ — even if the only one who ever reads it is me, and the sea, and whatever God I remember to believe in on the twenty-fifth.` },
        { type: 'em', text: `It\u2019s always her.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch1',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter One',
      title: 'The Boy Who Had Never Spoken to a Girl',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `To understand what she did to me, you have to understand what I was before her, which was: nothing that had ever been touched.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I grew up in Visakhapatnam — Vizag, if you have the accent for it — where the hills come down to meet the Bay of Bengal like they cannot quite believe their luck. It is a city of steel and salt. The steel plant on one side, throwing its orange glow against the night clouds so that even our darkness had a furnace in it; and on the other side, always, the sea, patient and grey-green and older than every complaint we brought to it. I was raised in a two-room flat on the third floor of a building the colour of weak tea, close enough to the water that on stormy nights the whole house smelled of salt and my mother would go around shutting windows that did not need shutting, just to feel she had done something against the weather.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `My father sold insurance. He rode a scooter the exact brown of an overripe banana and came home smelling of other people's futures — their fear of dying, their hope of leaving something behind. He was a gentle man who had made a career out of talking to strangers about the worst thing that could happen to them, and perhaps that is why, at home, he spoke so little. My mother spoke enough for both of them. She taught mathematics at a government school and believed, with the fierce and narrow faith of people who have clawed their way to a small security, that everything in life could be solved if you were only disciplined enough about it. Marks. Money. Marriage. In that order. She had a formula for all three.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And she had exactly one son to run the formula on.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `They sent me to a boys' school. Not out of any philosophy — it was simply the good school, the one with the results, the one where the fees hurt enough to feel like an investment. So from the age of five to the age of fifteen, my entire experience of the human race was male. Boys in the classroom, boys on the cricket ground, boys in the sweaty crush of the school bus, boys' laughter and boys' cruelty and the particular boys' loneliness that no one ever warns you about because boys are not supposed to be lonely, only bored.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Girls existed, of course. I had a cousin or two. I had a mother. But girls my own age, girls I might have _spoken_ to, girls as fellow travellers rather than rumours — these I did not have. They were a country I had heard described but never visited, and like all undiscovered countries, they grew more mythical the longer I stayed away. My friends and I discussed them the way sailors must once have discussed sea monsters: with enormous confidence and no data whatsoever.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `By fifteen I had constructed, without meaning to, a very specific kind of shyness. Not the loud shyness that draws sympathy. The quiet, engineered kind — the kind that hides inside a joke, that volunteers to be the funny one at the back so that no one looks too closely and discovers that the funny one has never, not once, held a conversation with a girl and would very possibly faint if required to.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `That was the boy. Fifteen years old, quick with a joke, dying inside of a thing he could not have named, standing at the gate of the eleventh grade the way you stand at the edge of a cold sea — knowing you will have to go in, and stalling.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `The school I moved to for the eleventh was different in the way that changes a life: it was _co-educational._` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I remember my mother saying the word at the dinner table, over rice and the thin tamarind rasam she made on Tuesdays, as though it were a minor administrative detail. _It is co-education,_ she said. _Better teachers. Better results. You will focus._ She said _you will focus_ the way other mothers say _God is watching_ — as a fact, a fence, and a threat, all at once. My father said nothing, but he passed me the extra papad, which was, in the grammar of our family, an entire speech of encouragement.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `That night I could not sleep. I lay on the floor of the front room, where I slept in summer because it caught what little breeze the city offered, and I stared at the ceiling fan turning its slow, useless circles, and I was afraid in a way I had no vocabulary for. I was not afraid of the syllabus. I was a good enough student; my mother had seen to that. I was afraid of _them._ Of walking into a room and finding half of it occupied by the mythical country, no longer myth, close enough to touch, close enough to disappoint.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I made a plan, the way frightened people make plans. I would find the last bench. I would find Ravi — my one certainty, my friend since we were seven and had bonded over a shared and total inability to catch a cricket ball — and I would sit beside him and be the funny one, safe and unremarkable, and I would get through two years without ever having to test whether I was the kind of boy a girl might notice.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `It was a good plan. It lasted, as it turned out, until roughly eleven o'clock on the first morning.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Ravi found me at the gate. He had grown over the summer into a lankier, louder version of himself, all elbows and opinions, and he greeted me by putting me in a headlock, which was his way of saying he had missed me. Ravi is important to this story, so let me set him down properly: he was the friend who feels no fear because he has never once imagined that the world might not want him. Where I calculated, he simply walked forward. Where I rehearsed sentences for hours and then did not say them, he said the wrong thing instantly and was forgiven instantly, because charm, I have learned, is mostly just the confidence to be wrong out loud.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CRelax,\u201D he told me, reading my face the way he always could. \u201CIt's just school. Same boredom, new decorations.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `_New decorations._ He meant the girls. He said it lightly, the way he said everything, and I laughed because I was supposed to, and we climbed the stairs to the eleventh-standard block with the whole terrible ordinary future waiting at the top of them.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Our classroom was on the second floor, a long room with high windows down one side that looked out over the play field and, beyond it, a smudge of the sea if you sat in the right place and the haze was kind. The last bench — my promised land — was in the far corner, under the last window. I took it like a man taking a lifeboat. Ravi dropped beside me. Two other boys we knew drifted over, and within ten minutes we had rebuilt, in that corner, the exact safe kingdom of noise I had lived inside for ten years.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I thought I had won. I thought I had successfully hidden.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I want to tell that boy — that specific boy, laughing too loudly at the back of a room on a warm morning in the eleventh grade — that hiding never saves anyone. That the universe has a particular fondness for boys who think they have arranged things safely, and that it was, at that very moment, opening a door two floors below and sending a girl up the stairs who was checking, with every step, whether she was late.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She was not late. She was, if anything, exactly on time.` },
        { type: 'em', text: `I was the one who was about to be late — late for the rest of my life.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch2',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Two',
      title: 'The Door and the Breeze',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `The teacher had not yet come. That is the first thing to know, because it means the room was in that particular state a classroom enters in the five minutes before authority arrives — loose, warm, unwatched, forty teenagers pretending to look for pens while actually taking the measure of one another for the first time.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I was mid-sentence in some story Ravi had demanded, my back half to the door, when the room changed. I did not see it change so much as _feel_ it, the way you feel a cloud cross the sun on the back of your neck. A small hush moved through the front rows and did not reach us at the back, so that for a second the room held two weathers at once.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The door had opened. Softly. The way you open a door when you are not certain the world will forgive you for being behind it.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `A girl peeped in first — just her face, just enough of her to check whether the teacher had come, whether she had judged the timing wrong, whether she would have to perform the small public humiliation of the late entrance. She had not judged it wrong. And having confirmed this, she stepped inside.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `I have tried, for ten years, to find an honest way to describe what happened next, and every honest way sounds like a lie, because the truth is embarrassing and enormous and does not care whether you believe it.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `At the exact second she stepped through the door, a breeze came in off the sea through the high windows on the left. It was nothing — a school breeze, smelling faintly of salt and cut grass and the tar of the play field. It lifted the corner of the map that hung by the blackboard and let it fall. It turned a page of somebody's open notebook. And it moved across her as she entered, so that a strand of her hair lifted and her cotton dupatta stirred and, for a single suspended instant, the whole ordinary morning arranged itself around her arrival as though it had been waiting all summer for exactly this cue.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I felt her reflection fall into my eyes. That is the only way I can put it, and I know how it sounds. Not her — her reflection, the light-print of her, the after-image you get from looking at something too bright. It fell into my eyes and it settled there and it has, in the most literal sense I am capable of meaning, never left.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She did not see me. Why would she? I was a boy at a back corner, one of a knot of noisy boys, indistinguishable from the general furniture of the male half of the room. Her eyes went where a new girl's eyes go — to the other girls, to the question of _where do I belong, who are my people here_ — and she found them almost at once, three girls near the middle who made room without being asked, the way girls do when they have already, silently, decided to take someone in. She slipped into the seat among them. She said something; one of them laughed; she became, within the space of a minute, a natural and permanent feature of the classroom, as though she had always been there and I had simply failed, until now, to notice the obvious.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `But I had noticed. That was the trouble. I had noticed with a completeness that frightened me.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CYou've stopped talking,\u201D Ravi observed.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I had. Mid-story, mid-sentence, mid-life. I picked the sentence back up and finished it badly, and Ravi looked at me with the beginnings of a grin, because Ravi missed nothing that could later be used against you affectionately, and I turned my face to the window and pretended enormous interest in the play field, where nothing at all was happening.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The teacher came. The morning began. Names were called from a register in the flat, ceremonial voice teachers use on first days, and I sat very still through the alphabet, waiting, though I could not have told you what I was waiting for. And then, near the middle of the list, the teacher said her name.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I am not going to write it here. I have kept it unwritten for ten years and I find I cannot spend it now, not even in a book only I will read; some coins you keep precisely because you will never be rich enough to want to break them. So let me do what I have always done in the private ledger of my own head, and call her by the single letter I have loved longer than I have loved anything else.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `_V._ She answered _present_ in a voice that was lower than I expected, and calmer, a voice with no need to be heard, and something in me that had been standing on tiptoe all morning quietly sat down and made itself at home for the next decade.` },
        { type: 'verse', lines: [
          `Some loves arrive with thunder and with drums;`,
          `mine came in through a door left half ajar —`,
          `she leaned inside to see if she was late,`,
          `and I was late, from then, for who I are.`,
        ] },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `I learned her, that first term, the way you learn a language you are not allowed to admit you are studying.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I learned that she was calm in a way that was almost a kind of power. The rest of us, at sixteen, were performing constantly — performing coolness, performing boredom, performing a confidence none of us owned. She did not perform. She sat inside herself, unhurried, and let the room come to her, and it did. When the loud girls laughed too loudly, she smiled a smaller, private smile, as if she found the whole business of being sixteen gently amusing and was content to wait for it to pass. When a teacher asked a hard question and the room went into its usual defensive silence, she would answer — not to show off, never that, but simply because she knew the answer and saw no reason to pretend otherwise. There is a particular kind of person who does not need you to think well of them, and it makes you think well of them helplessly. She was that kind.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I learned her handwriting, from a distance — round, unhurried letters that leaned very slightly backward, as though even her sentences were in no rush to arrive. I learned that she tucked her hair behind her ear with two fingers, always two, always the right hand, usually just before she began to write. I learned that she was kind in the undramatic way that is the only kind that counts: she was the one who noticed the new-transfer girl eating lunch alone and simply sat down beside her, without announcement, without wanting credit, and had, by the end of the week, folded her quietly into the group.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I learned, most dangerously of all, that watching her cost me nothing and gave me everything, and that this exchange rate would ruin me.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CYou know you're doing it again,\u201D Ravi said, a few weeks in. We were walking home along the beach road, the evening going gold and then grey over the water, the fishing boats coming in as small dark commas against the horizon.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CDoing what.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CThe thing. The staring-into-the-distance, writing-poetry-in-your-head thing. You've been weird since the first day.\u201D He kicked a stone off the pavement into the sand. \u201CIt's the new girl. The quiet one.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I have never been a good liar, and I was a spectacularly bad one at sixteen. I said, \u201CI don't know what you're talking about,\u201D and my voice did something humiliating on the second word, and Ravi laughed the laugh of a man who has just won a small bet with himself.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201COh no,\u201D he said, delighted, awful, my dearest friend in the world. \u201COh, this is going to be a whole thing, isn't it.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I did not answer him. Below us the sea kept doing what it does, indifferent and eternal, folding itself onto the sand and drawing back, folding and drawing back, keeping a rhythm older than any of our small human aches. I remember thinking, with the doomed clarity you sometimes get at sixteen, that I would probably never say a single word to her. That I was too new to this, too afraid, too much a boy assembled entirely out of jokes and silences. That whatever this was would live and die inside my own chest and she would go through her whole life without ever knowing she had, on a warm ordinary morning, walked in through a door and taken a boy at the back of the room quietly and completely apart.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I was wrong about a great many things, at sixteen. But that year I was wrong about the biggest one of all — because a few weeks later, in a corridor between two classes, with no breeze and no ceremony and no warning at all, she would look directly at me, and she would say the smallest, largest word in any language.` },
        { type: 'em', text: `But that is the next chapter, and I am not ready to leave this one yet.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch3',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Three',
      title: 'The First Hi',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `There is a first time for everything, and most of them you forget. The first time you rode a bicycle without a hand on the seat behind you. The first time you understood that your parents were people, and frightened, and making it up as they went. You forget these because life buries them under a thousand ordinary days.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `But there is one first I will carry out of this world with me, and it happened in a corridor that smelled of chalk and floor polish and the particular boredom of the hour after lunch.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `It was a Wednesday. I know it was a Wednesday because Wednesdays we had chemistry in the far block, which meant the long walk down the second-floor corridor with the arched windows, and I had learned — the way you learn the tide tables of your own small obsession — that her class let out at the same time as mine, and that if I walked neither too fast nor too slow, we would pass somewhere near the middle, by the notice board no one ever read.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I had been doing this for weeks. Engineering coincidences. Standing at the exact intersection of our timetables and pretending to be surprised by geography. I never spoke. Speaking was not part of the plan; the plan was only to _be near_, to spend a few seconds inside the same stretch of air she was in, and then to carry those seconds home and live off them like a miser living off a single coin.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `That Wednesday, she was walking with Meera.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Meera you will need to know, because she becomes, much later, the person who hands me the truth I had given up hoping for. But then she was only V's closest friend — a small, sharp, laughing girl who noticed everything and forgave most of it. Where V was still water, Meera was the stone you throw in: she made things happen, she said the unsayable, she was the engine in every plan the girls ever made. I was frightened of her in the specific way you are frightened of people who see clearly.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `They were coming toward me, the two of them, heads bent together over some private joke, and I did what I always did — I fixed my eyes on the middle distance and arranged my face into the blank of a boy going somewhere important. Three steps. Two. And in the half-second we drew level, V lifted her head, and she looked directly at me — not past me, not through me, _at_ me, at the boy from the back corner she had, apparently, noticed after all — and she said it.` },
        { type: 'em', text: `\u201CHi.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `One syllable. A single soft consonant and a vowel, the smallest unit of hello the language allows.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I want you to understand what that word did, and to understand it you have to remember the boy I have already shown you — fifteen years in a world of boys, girls a rumour, the whole female half of creation a country he had never once been greeted in. No girl outside my own blood had ever said that word to my face and meant _you_. And now one had. Not just any one. _Her._ The word came out of her the way water comes out of a spring, easy, unforced, costing her nothing — and it landed on me with the weight of a coronation.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I said something back. I have tried for ten years to recover exactly what, and I cannot, because the machinery that records such things had briefly caught fire. I believe it was \u201Chi.\u201D I believe I managed to return her one syllable with one syllable of my own, which under the circumstances was a feat roughly equivalent to composing a symphony while drowning. Meera glanced at me with a flicker of amusement, filed something away, and then they were past, and the corridor closed behind them, and I stood there like a man who has just been struck gently by lightning and found that it did not hurt at all but had rearranged, permanently, the wiring of his heart.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Ravi was waiting at the chemistry lab. He took one look at me and said, \u201CWhat happened to your face.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CNothing.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CYou look like you saw God.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CShe said hi,\u201D I told him, and the sentence came out of me in a kind of wonder, and Ravi — who had said hi to nine hundred girls and been said hi to by nine hundred more, for whom the transaction was as unremarkable as breathing — looked at me for a long moment, and something shifted in his face, some understanding of just how strange and total this was for me, and to his eternal credit he did not laugh. He put his hand on my shoulder like a man steadying a friend at a funeral or a wedding, the two occasions that ask the same tenderness, and he said, \u201COkay. Okay. This is serious, then.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CIt's serious,\u201D I agreed.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `It was the truest thing either of us had ever said.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `After that Wednesday, something loosened. Not much — I was still me, still the boy who could rehearse a sentence for an hour and then swallow it — but a small door had been propped open, and through it began to pass a currency I had not known existed.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `We developed, V and I, a language with almost no words in it.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `It went like this. We would pass — in the corridor, at the morning assembly, in the crush at the gate when the last bell had gone and eight hundred children tried to become free at the same instant — and she would _wink_. Quick, light, one eye, there and gone, the kind of wink that some people are simply born knowing how to give, that means nothing in particular and therefore everything. And I would smile. That was the whole of it. A wink, and a smile in reply. To anyone watching it was nothing, was less than nothing, was two schoolmates acknowledging each other's existence with the minimum civility the day required.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `To me it was correspondence. It was a letter arriving every day, addressed in a hand only I could read. I built entire afternoons on a single wink. I lay on the floor of the front room at night, the fan turning its slow circles, and I replayed it — the exact tilt of her head, the exact speed of the eye, the exact and unbearable ease of it — and I thought, with the doomed grandeur of sixteen, that I would trade every word I would ever be given for the certainty of one more wink tomorrow.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I got one tomorrow. And the day after. For a while, the arithmetic of my happiness was that simple, and I was, God help me, entirely and stupidly content.` },
        { type: 'verse', lines: [
          `You spent one word, and bankrupted the boy`,
          `who had never been greeted, never been seen;`,
          `a wink in a corridor, a smile in reply —`,
          `our whole tongue, and I was fluent, and sixteen.`,
        ] },
        { type: 'p', text: `I should have known that a happiness built on so little would, sooner or later, be tested by the world. The world does not like to see a boy content on a diet of winks. It prefers to complicate things.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And a few weeks later, in the poisonous way that rumours move through a school, it did.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch4',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Four',
      title: 'The Arithmetic of Benches',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `Weekend exams were my secret festival, and to explain why, I have to explain the seating.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `On ordinary days we sat where we always sat — me in my corner, her in her middle, a whole classroom of fixed orbits. But for exams they broke the orbits. They rearranged us by roll number or by some private logic of the invigilators, mixed the sections, scattered us across the hall in new and temporary constellations. Everyone else groaned at this. I lived for it. Because the rearranging was a lottery, and the prize, on a good day, was proximity.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `So while my classmates spent the night before an exam memorising formulae, I spent part of it doing a different and more desperate mathematics. I would try to guess the seating. I would count benches in my head, run the roll numbers, calculate the odds that her seat and mine might fall on the same long wooden line. I prayed, on exam nights, to a God I otherwise troubled only during cricket finals — _let her be near, let the lottery be kind, I will learn the chapter, I promise, only let her be near._` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Sometimes the God of exam halls answered.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She would be placed a bench ahead and to the left, close enough that I could hear the small sounds of her concentration — the tick of her pen, the sigh she gave when a question was unfair, the way she tucked her hair behind her ear with two fingers before she began to write. And I would sit with an unopened question paper and discover that every formula I had crammed the night before had quietly left the building, because you cannot hold trigonometry and her at the same time; there is not room in a boy for both.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I never spoke, in those halls. Speaking was forbidden, which was a mercy, because it gave my cowardice a legal excuse. So I did the only brave thing a coward is permitted — I looked. Carefully. From behind the shield of a raised answer sheet, from the far corner of an eye, in the two seconds an invigilator's back was turned. A thousand small glances that added up, over two years, to a confession I never once made aloud. I passed those exams, mostly. I have often thought that I passed them the way a sleepwalker crosses a busy road — by some grace that had nothing to do with attention.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `And then, one grey December morning, the lottery gave me everything at once. Not a bench ahead. The same bench. Hers and mine.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I do not know how I sat down. I remember the wood was cold through my trousers and that she had arrived first and arranged her things with the calm competence she brought to everything — two pens, a pencil, a small transparent geometry box, all laid out like a surgeon's instruments. I remember she looked up when I sat, and gave me not the corridor wink but something quieter, a small real smile of recognition, _oh, it's you_, and that this smile was somehow more than the wink because it had no audience, it was spent on me alone, and I have kept it.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The paper began. For twenty minutes we wrote in the roaring silence of an exam hall, elbow to elbow, two strangers who were not strangers, and I was so aware of the eighteen inches between her arm and mine that I could have told you the temperature of them.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And then, halfway down the second page, she leaned an inch toward me and, in the smallest whisper the hall would allow, she asked if she could borrow a pen. Hers had died.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `I had two pens. One was a cheap thing that skipped and blotted. The other was good — a smooth dark-blue rollerball my father had brought me from a conference, the nicest object I owned, the pen I used for exams because it made even my ordinary handwriting look like it meant something.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I gave her the good one. I did not even decide to; my hand decided, ahead of my brain, the way the body always knows first. And then, because I had given away my only working pen, I took out my pencil and wrote the rest of my own examination in grey — faint, smudging, the side of my hand dragging silver across every line, a paper that looked, when I handed it in, like something recovered from a shipwreck.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I did not care. I have rarely in my life cared less about anything. Because a bench away, moving steadily down her own paper, her answers were coming out in _my_ ink. My dark blue, in her round unhurried hand. And it seemed to me — it still seems to me — one of the most intimate things that has ever happened to me, that for one December morning her thoughts wore my ink to the page, and neither of us said a word about it, and both of us, I am almost sure, knew.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She gave the pen back at the end, of course. \u201CThank you,\u201D she said, and I said \u201Cany time,\u201D two more words for the record, and I put the pen in my pocket and did not use it again for a month, because it had been hers for an hour and I was not ready to write over that.` },
        { type: 'verse', lines: [
          `Others wrote answers; I wrote your name in the white`,
          `unmarked margins the invigilators can't see.`,
          `You asked; I gave you my ink and finished in grey —`,
          `I would fail every paper on earth to be blue in your reply.`,
        ] },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `I have made that season sound like an unbroken idyll, and I should not, because it was during that same winter that I learned what jealousy tastes like, which is: like biting the inside of your own cheek, a small private blood you cannot stop returning to.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The rumour came the way rumours come, sideways, from a boy who had heard it from a girl who had heard it from someone who would know. That V liked someone. A boy from the twelfth, a cricketer, tall, easy, the sort of boy the world hands things to. That they had been seen. That it was, more or less, understood.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I cannot describe to you the completeness of the ruin this caused in me, because nothing had actually happened — I had no claim, no right, not even a friendship worth the name, only a wink and a borrowed pen and a private cathedral I had built out of both. I had no standing to be jealous. And yet I lay on the floor that night and the fan turned and I felt something I had never felt, a cold green thing that ate the winks and the smile and the ink and left me with nothing but the certainty that of course, _of course_, a girl like that was already spoken for by the visible world, while I loved her from a corner in a language of one.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Ravi found me hollow the next day and dragged the reason out of me on the beach road, and when I told him he was quiet for a while, watching the boats, and then he said the thing that I have needed, at intervals, for the rest of my life. \u201CYou don't actually know anything,\u201D he said. \u201CYou've built a whole tragedy out of a sentence a fool told you. Go and look at the facts before you bury yourself.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The facts, when they arrived, were merciful. The rumour was a rumour — a crossed wire, a misread friendship, the cricketer belonged to someone else entirely, and V, it turned out, had laughed when Meera told her what the school was saying. She had _laughed._ I heard about the laugh secondhand and I treasured it unreasonably, because a girl who laughs at the rumour of a boyfriend is a girl who has not, at least, given her heart to the visible world, and the corner from which I loved her was not, after all, a completely foolish place to stand.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `But the jealousy taught me something the winks never could. It taught me that this was not a hobby. That a thing which can hollow you out over a stranger's careless sentence is not a crush; it is a foundation, and I had, without permission and without hope, poured mine.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch5',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Five',
      title: 'The Chocolates and the Handshake',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `And then came the twenty-fifth of December, though I did not yet know that the date would become the axis my whole life would quietly turn on. That first year it was simply her birthday, and in the small economy of our school, a birthday had a ritual.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The custom was this: the birthday child was not the one who received. The birthday child _gave_. She would come to school with a box — chocolates, usually, the small foil-wrapped kind — and go around the classroom bestowing sweetness on the people she counted as hers. It was a public act of accounting, a girl's private ledger made briefly visible: watch, and you would learn exactly who mattered to her, and in what order, and how much.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I had spent the days before it telling myself not to hope. I was not on any ledger. I was the boy at the back who had once been handed a pen; I was corridor winks and nothing that could be written down. She would go to her girls, to Meera, to the friends who ringed her like planets, and she would not cross the room to its far corner, and that would be correct, and I would survive it.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `She came in that morning in a chudidhar.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I have tried to describe it many times and I always fail, so let me fail honestly. She did not wear it the way the other girls wore their finery on such days — as an announcement, a thing to be looked at. She wore it the way she wore everything, as if it were simply the truth of her that morning, and the effect of that, the effect of beauty worn without the slightest demand that you notice it, is the most devastating effect there is. The ordinary classroom, the cracked green board, the map with its curling corner — all of it seemed suddenly to be apologising for how plain it was around her. I forgot to breathe in the professional, practised way I had of forgetting to breathe around her, and simply sat, undone, at the back.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She began her round with the box. Meera first, of course. Then the ring of girls, then some of the boys she was easy with, the loud safe ones, laughter following her like a small weather. I kept my eyes on my notebook and drew nothing in it very carefully and told my heart, which had started up its foolish hoping, to sit down.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And then a shadow fell across the page, and I looked up, and she was standing at my bench.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `She held out the box. \u201CTake,\u201D she said — that was all, _take_, the plainest word — and she was smiling the small private smile, and I understood, with a lurch that went all the way down, that I was on the ledger after all. That in the accounting of who mattered to her, the boy at the back corner had a line, however far down, however small the sum.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I took a chocolate. My fingers did not quite work. I said something — \u201Chappy birthday,\u201D I think, the standard coin, but I meant it the way you mean a prayer, with my whole spine. And then, because some reckless committee in me had seized control of the body while the rest of me was still stunned, I did a thing I had never done in my life.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I put out my hand.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `For a handshake. As if we were two small executives closing a deal. It was, I see now, an absurd gesture, a boy who did not know what to do with a feeling reaching for the only formal thing he had, the one ritual of contact he had ever been taught was allowed. And for a terrible half-second it hung there in the air between us, my offered hand, and I thought, _you fool, you have ruined it, she will laugh, or worse she will be kind about it_ —` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And then she took it.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Her hand was in mine. I want to slow this down because I have slowed it down ten thousand times, so let me do it once on paper. It was the first time in my life I had held the hand of a girl I was not related to by blood. An unknown hand, a girl's hand, smaller than mine and warmer, certain in a way mine was not, because mine was shaking — actually, visibly shaking, a tremor I could not stop, running up from somewhere below my own knowledge of myself. I was terrified. I was more awake than I had ever been. Every nerve I owned had come to the surface of that one square of skin.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `It lasted two seconds. Perhaps three. A handshake, nothing more, the most sexless and formal of all human contacts, the thing you do with bank managers. And my body remembers those three seconds more completely than it remembers whole years of my life — remembers the warmth, the slight firmness of her grip, the impossible ordinariness of it for her and the seismic event of it for me, two people doing entirely different things with the same gesture, she being polite and I being permanently altered.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Then she let go, and moved on with her box, and the morning closed over the moment as though it had not just cracked the world down the middle. She did not know. That is the whole ache of it, and the whole beauty. She handed a chocolate and a handshake to a boy on her birthday and thought nothing of it, and walked on, and never once suspected that she had just given him a relic he would carry, warm, in the palm of his memory, for the rest of his life.` },
        { type: 'verse', lines: [
          `On your own day, you were the one who gave —`,
          `sweetness in one hand, and, for a heartbeat, your hand in mine.`,
          `I had never held a stranger's hand before;`,
          `it shook, as though it already knew it would not let go inside.`,
        ] },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `That night I could not sleep, which by then was ordinary, but the sleeplessness had a new shape. I lay on the floor and held my own right hand in my left, foolishly, as if I could keep the warmth in it, and I thought about the date. The twenty-fifth of December. I turned the numbers over like stones. And somewhere in that turning, without deciding it, I made a quiet promise to a girl who would never hear it: that whatever else the years did to us, wherever they scattered us, I would find her on this date. That once a year, at least, I would be allowed to light a small lamp and say her name into the dark and call it a birthday wish, and no one, not distance, not time, not even her own not-knowing, could take that one day from me.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I did not know, that first December, that I was making a vow. I thought I was just a boy who couldn't sleep, holding his own hand.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Ten Decembers later, the lamp is still lit. I have never missed one. But I am getting ahead of the story, and there is an ending to the eleventh and twelfth grades still to come — an ending that scatters us, and breaks something, and teaches me the exact weight of a sentence left unsaid.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch6',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Six',
      title: 'Two Roads Out of Twelfth',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `The twelfth grade ends the way all of school ends — suddenly, and without asking whether your heart is ready. One week you are inside a life that feels permanent, the benches and the bells and the corridor winks, the whole architecture of your days; and the next week a man in an office is stamping papers that dissolve it, and you understand that the permanence was a trick, that it was always only borrowed, that you have spent two years assuming you had time.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The board exams came first, and swallowed everything. For three months the school went quiet and grim, forty children bent over ten years of accumulated syllabus, and even I — even I, who had spent two years unable to hold trigonometry and her in the same mind — put my head down and worked, because my mother's formula had reached its decisive term and there was no arguing with it. _Marks. Money. Marriage. In that order._ The marks were now.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I saw less of V in those months. We were in different exam halls, on different revision schedules, and the corridor where we had built our wordless language emptied out as the classes dissolved into study leave. The winks grew rare, then rarer, then became a memory I checked on the way you check a scar. I told myself it was only the season. I told myself that after the exams there would be time. I have noticed, since, that _after this there will be time_ is the most expensive sentence a human being can say to himself, and that the bill always comes.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `The results came, and with them the scattering.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `This is how it worked, for my generation, in my city: you sat one more set of exams, the entrance ones, and a number came out of them, and the number decided your life with the cold efficiency of a sorting machine. It sent this one to Hyderabad and that one to Chennai; it sent the bright ones far and the ordinary ones near; it took a class that had been a single organism for two years and flung its cells across the whole map of the south, and it did not care, the machine, which of those cells had spent two years quietly orbiting which other.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `V's number sent her inland, to a good college in another city, to study the sciences she was made for. Mine sent me to an engineering college a few hours down the coast — near enough to smell the same sea, far enough that I would not, in the ordinary run of things, ever accidentally see her again. We would be, from that summer, two people who had once shared a bench, living in two different cities, joined by nothing but a phone number and the fraying thread of a friendship I had never even had the courage to properly begin.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Ravi, who was going to the same engineering college as me — the one mercy in the sorting — put it plainly on the beach road, the evening the lists came out. \u201CSo that's it, then,\u201D he said. \u201CUnless you do something, that's the last of her. You know that. After this everybody says they'll stay in touch, and nobody does, and in two years you won't even have her number saved under the right name.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CWhat am I supposed to do,\u201D I said.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `He looked at me like the answer was written on my forehead in a language I was refusing to read. \u201CTell her,\u201D he said. \u201CBefore she gets on that train. Just once in your life, say the thing instead of writing poetry about it in your head. What is the worst that happens? She says no, and you go to college with a clean wound instead of a question you'll pick at for the rest of your life. I'm telling you, brother — the no you can survive. It's the not-knowing that kills people slowly.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I have thought about that speech for ten years. He was right. He was completely, prophetically right, and I was eighteen and terrified, and I did not listen.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `But I tried. I want that on the record too. I did not simply let her go without a fight; I fought, in the only way a boy like me knew how, which was on paper, in private, where it was safe.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I wrote her a letter.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I wrote it over four nights, on the floor of the front room, by the light of my phone so my mother would not see the lamp and ask questions I had no answers for. I wrote it and tore it up and wrote it again. The first draft was a catalogue — the door, the breeze, the pen, the handshake, two years of winks — everything, laid out, as if the sheer weight of evidence could compel a verdict. The second draft was a poem, and terrible. The third draft I burned in the sense that matters, which is that I read it and understood it was true and could not bear how true it was. The fourth draft was three lines. I will not tell you what they were. They are the only three lines I have ever written that said exactly what I meant, and they have never been read by the person they were written for, and that is the great unhealed thing at the centre of this book.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I folded the fourth draft into a square and I put it in my shirt pocket, over the heart, like a fool in a film, and I went to the farewell.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `The farewell was loud and bright and unbearable. The whole cohort in their best clothes, teachers pretending not to cry, everyone signing everyone's shirts in fat marker, the forced hilarity of people who know they are at an ending and are trying to outrun it with noise. I moved through it with the letter burning a hole over my heart, looking for a moment, the moment, the clean quiet minute in which I would take her aside and simply hand it to her and let the three lines do what I had never been able to.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The moment did not come. Or it came, and I let it pass, which is the same thing dressed in a kinder word. She was always surrounded — Meera at her side, the ring of girls, the loud boys orbiting, the teachers wanting photographs with the topper. And every time the ring thinned and I gathered myself and started across the room, some new person would arrive to claim her, and I would veer off and pretend I had been going somewhere else, and the letter would stay in my pocket, and my courage, such as it was, would leak away a little more.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Once — once — we were almost alone. Near the end, by the notice board where our corridor language had been born, the crowd briefly pulled back, and it was just the two of us in a pocket of quiet, and she turned to me and smiled the small private smile, the one with no audience, and said, \u201CSo. Different cities now.\u201D And my hand actually moved toward my pocket, actually touched the folded square of paper — and she went on, easily, kindly, before I could — \u201CI'm really glad I knew you these two years. You're one of the good ones, you know that? A genuinely good person. I hope we stay in touch.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `_A genuinely good person._ _One of the good ones._` },
        { type: 'p', text: `You would have to have been that boy, in that pocket of quiet, to understand how those kind words closed a door as gently and completely as any cruelty could have. Because a girl does not say _you're one of the good ones_ to a boy whose letter she is waiting for. She says it to a friend. She says it to file him, warmly, permanently, in the drawer marked _safe_. And I heard the drawer slide shut, and my hand came away from my pocket empty, and I said, \u201CYeah. Me too. Stay in touch,\u201D and I smiled the smile of a man agreeing to his own sentence.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The letter stayed in my pocket. It is, as far as such things can be, still there.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `There was one more chance, and I ruined it more actively, which is somehow worse.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `That night — the last night, before the trains and buses of the next morning began carrying everyone away to their sorted futures — I could not sleep, and around midnight, in a fit of the courage that only ever visits me when it is too late to be useful, I called her.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She answered on the fourth ring, her voice soft with almost-sleep, and there was a moment, hearing that unguarded voice in the dark, when the three lines rose all the way to my throat and I thought, _now, say it now, there is no ring of girls now, no notice board, no farewell, just her voice and the dark and the truth, say it._` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And she said, before I could — happy, sleepy, entirely innocent of what she was interrupting — \u201CKiaan? Is everything okay? It's so late.\u201D And she used the name, the soft one, _Kiaan_, which she had started calling me somewhere in the second year and which no one else in the world used, and hearing it in her sleep-soft voice at midnight was so much, was so unbearably much, that the courage that had carried the three lines all the way to my throat simply broke, and what came out instead was, \u201CYeah — no — everything's fine, I just — I wanted to say good luck. For the new college. That's all.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `A silence. Then, warm, \u201CThat's so sweet. Good luck to you too, Kiaan. Now sleep, okay? Big day tomorrow.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201COkay,\u201D I said. \u201CGoodnight.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CGoodnight.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And she hung up, and I lay on the floor with the phone still warm against my ear and the three lines sinking back down into the place they have lived ever since, and I understood — with a completeness that eighteen-year-olds are not supposed to be capable of — that I had just let the single clean chance of my life go by, out of nothing braver than fear, and that some part of me would spend a very long time standing on that midnight, hand on the letter, mouth full of the unsaid, watching the door slide shut.` },
        { type: 'verse', lines: [
          `I wrote you four letters and gave you none;`,
          `I carried the truth to my throat and swallowed it whole.`,
          `You called me one of the good ones, and shut, so kindly, a door —`,
          `and I have been the boy on that midnight ever since, my whole soul.`,
        ] },
        { type: 'p', text: `In the morning the trains left. Mine went south down the coast; hers went inland into the dry bright plains. We waved, I think. We said we would stay in touch. And love, I was about to learn, does not die of distance — it does something far stranger. It goes underground, and it waits, and it burns very low and very blue, and it keeps a calendar.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch7',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Seven',
      title: 'The Twenty-Fifth of December',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `Here is a thing they do not tell you about a love that never became anything: it is the easiest kind to keep, because there is nothing to maintain. A real relationship needs feeding — attention, presence, the daily small repairs. Mine needed only a calendar. It asked nothing of me for three hundred and sixty-four days a year. And on the three hundred and sixty-fifth, it asked only that I remember, and I have never in my life had trouble remembering her.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `College took me, as college takes everyone, and remade me. I want to be honest about this, because it would be a lie to paint the next years as a boy sitting in the dark pining. I did not pine. I lived. I found, in the engineering college down the coast, a version of myself I had not met before — one who could talk, finally, who had learned somewhere in the wreckage of that farewell that if he was going to lose the people he loved by staying silent, he might as well lose the fear instead. The last-bench boy did not survive the first year of college. In his place grew someone easier, funnier out loud instead of only in his head, someone who could sit across from a girl and hold a conversation without his voice betraying him on the second word.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And yet. At the back of all of it, behind the new friends and the late-night canteen arguments and the slow confident unfolding of a personality, there burned that low blue flame. Never high. Never in the way. Just — lit. A pilot light at the back of the stove of my life, warming a small room no one else could see, kept alive by nothing but a phone number I never deleted and a date I never forgot.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `The ritual established itself without my ever deciding on it.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The first December after school, I told myself I would just send a normal wish, the kind everyone sends, casual, deniable. I drafted it for an hour. I sent it at eleven fifty-eight, two minutes before midnight, because some superstition in me wanted to be early, wanted the wish waiting for her when the day turned rather than arriving late in the general flood. She replied the next morning: _thank you so much Kiaan! how are you, how's college?_ And we talked for a little while, that first year, easy and warm, two friends catching up. It cost me nothing and it fed the pilot light for months.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The second December, I did it again. And the third. And somewhere in there it stopped being a thing I decided to do and became a thing that simply happened to me, the way the tide happens to the shore — the calendar would turn toward the twenty-fifth and her name would rise in me like water that knows its hour, and at midnight, wherever I was, whatever wreckage or joy my own life was passing through, I would type the message and send it into the dark.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The replies changed over the years, and I read them the way an old sailor reads weather. Some years she wrote back long and warm, and I lived on it. Some years just _thank you_, polite, brief, a door open only a crack, and I lived on that too, because I had long ago made my peace with living on very little. One year — a bad year, a year when we had not spoken in months — she did not reply at all for three days, and then sent, simply, _sorry, saw this late. thank you, Kiaan. means a lot that you always remember._ And I read _you always remember_ forty times and heard in it the one thing I needed, which was that she had noticed the pattern, that somewhere in her accounting of the world there was a small entry that said _he never misses._` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Ten Decembers. Not one missed. Through her college and mine, through my first job and her master's applications, through the years we talked weekly and the years we did not talk at all, through two relationships of mine and God knows what of hers — the lamp got lit, the message got sent, the small annual prayer got said. It was never a transaction. I did not send it hoping for a reply, though the replies were the wine of my whole year. I sent it because it was the one devotion I was allowed, the one place where the thing I felt could go out into the world and touch her, however lightly, once, before folding itself back up for another year.` },
        { type: 'verse', lines: [
          `The world forgets a thousand dates;`,
          `my heart has memorised only one.`,
          `On the twenty-fifth, without a fail,`,
          `I light a lamp for a girl who cannot see that it has begun.`,
        ] },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `It was in the third year of college that Ananya arrived, though I did not understand, for a long time, what she was — or rather, what I was to her. That is the cruelty of the thing, and its symmetry: I was so busy being the boy who loved from a corner that I did not notice, for the better part of a year, that a girl had begun to love me from one.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She was in my department. Sharp, quick, quietly funny in a way you had to be paying attention to catch. We fell into an easy friendship — lab partners first, then the kind of friends who save each other seats and share notes and drift, in a crowd, toward each other without deciding to. She laughed at my jokes a beat before the punchline, the way you laugh at someone whose mind you have learned. She remembered things I had said in passing weeks before. She was, I see now with the terrible clarity of hindsight, doing every single thing I had done at sixteen — the small engineered coincidences, the attention disguised as friendship, the whole careful architecture of a person orbiting another and calling it something safer than what it was.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I, who had written the manual on that architecture, did not read it in her, because I was facing the other way. I was still turned toward an inland city and a phone that lit up once a year. I liked Ananya enormously. I did not love her. And I had no idea — none — that I had become, in someone else's story, the girl at the door. The one who winks in the corridor and thinks nothing of it. The one who hands over a chocolate and a handshake and walks on, never suspecting what she has done.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I was about to learn what my love looked like from the other side of the bench. And it would be the most painful education of my life.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch8',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Eight',
      title: 'The Years That Tried to Replace Her',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `I did try to move on. I need you to believe that, because everything I am about to tell you depends on it. This is not the story of a boy who sat faithfully in the dark for ten years, guarding a flame like a monk. I tried, honestly and repeatedly, to love someone who could love me back, and the trying is its own chapter, and not a proud one.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `There were two, in the years I am telling you about. Two relationships that I entered with real hope and left having learned something I would rather not have learned about the geometry of my own heart.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `The first was Ananya, though it took me most of a year to understand that the friendship had a second floor she had been living on alone.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She told me on a rooftop, at the end of our third year, at one of those late gatherings that colleges produce — a dozen of us on the terrace of somebody's rented room, string lights and cheap music and the particular tenderness of people who know they have one more year and then the sorting machine again. The others had drifted down; it was just the two of us at the parapet, the city spread out below, and she said it without any of the elaborate cowardice I would have brought to it. She just said it. That she had felt this way for a long time. That she thought I might have felt it too, or could. That she was tired of pretending the friendship was the whole of it when for her it had never been.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I stood there on that rooftop, and I felt the ground tilt, because I recognised everything. I recognised the tremble under her steady voice — I had trembled exactly that way, holding out my hand for a handshake, four years before. I recognised the courage it had cost her to say the thing out loud, because I had failed to find that same courage on a midnight phone call and had paid for the failure every day since. She was doing the brave thing I had never done. She was handing me her letter, the one I had folded into my pocket and never delivered, and she was watching my face for the verdict.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I could not give her the answer she deserved. Because when I looked inside myself for the feeling that would have made it true, I found instead a low blue flame burning toward an inland city, and I understood, standing on that rooftop, with the kindest girl I knew looking at me with her whole heart in her face, that I was not free to give. That some fool at the age of sixteen had signed the deed to this ground away to a girl who did not even know she held it, and that I had no right to build here, on Ananya's rooftop, a house I did not own.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `I tried anyway. That is the part I am least proud of. Because she was wonderful, and there in front of me, and real in a way V had not been real for years, and I thought — the way you think when you are twenty and lonely and want so badly to be a normal boy with a normal heart — I thought that maybe love could be _decided._ That if I chose her, and was good to her, the feeling would follow the choice the way water follows a channel you dig for it.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `We were together for the better part of a year. And she was, for a while, happy, and I was, for a while, almost convinced. But you cannot dig a channel to a sea that is already flowing somewhere else, and she was too sharp not to feel the current under everything, the way I was always, very slightly, faced away. She never found out about V — there was nothing to find, no rival she could point to, which somehow made it worse, because how do you fight a girl who is not even in the city, who exists only as a name that lights up a phone one night a year? She only knew that some inner room of me was locked, and that no matter how she loved me, she was never quite given the key.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She ended it, in the end, and she was right to. \u201CYou're a good person, Kiaan,\u201D she said — and there it was again, the exact words V had used on me, the drawer marked _safe_, handed to me now from the other side — \u201Cbut you're not _here._ You're lovely, and you're kind, and you're somewhere else, and I can't keep loving a person who's standing next to me and looking over my shoulder at someone I can't see.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I did not have an answer. She had described me exactly.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Here is what that year gave me, at Ananya's cost, and I have never stopped being sorry for the price she paid for my education: it let me stand, at last, on the other side of the bench. It let me be the one who is loved and cannot love back. It let me feel, from the inside, what V must feel — if she feels anything at all — when a good and faithful boy turns his whole heart toward her and she has only kindness to offer in return.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I learned that it is not cruelty. That was the revelation that undid me. I had spent years, in my lowest moments, privately accusing V — of blindness, of carelessness, of not seeing what was in front of her. And now here was Ananya's whole heart in front of _me_, and I saw it clearly, I saw it completely, and I still could not manufacture the feeling that would have made her happy, because the feeling is not a decision. It cannot be summoned by will or earned by merit or deserved into being. It simply is, or it is not. V was not cruel to me. She was only, like me on that rooftop, faced the other way, toward some sea of her own I would never be allowed to see.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The second relationship came a year later, after college, in the early grey grind of my first job. It was gentler and sadder and shorter, and it ended the same way, for the same reason, and I will not make you sit through it, because it taught me nothing the rooftop had not already carved into me. Except this, perhaps: that I was becoming a danger to good women. That as long as that low blue flame burned at the back of me, I would keep letting people who deserved a whole heart settle for a house with one locked room, and that the kindest thing I could do for the next Ananya was to stop pretending I was free.` },
        { type: 'verse', lines: [
          `I stood where you stand, and was loved as I love you,`,
          `and found I could not turn my face from the sea.`,
          `So I stopped blaming you for the drawer marked safe —`,
          `for now I keep the same drawer, and the same locked key.`,
        ] },
        { type: 'p', text: `After the second one ended, I stopped trying for a while. Not out of loyalty — I want to be precise about this, because it would be romantic and false to call it loyalty. I stopped because I had finally understood the shape of my own heart, and it was not a shape that could be forced, and I was tired of breaking good people against it. The compass would keep turning north no matter which direction I walked. I could fight it, and hurt everyone in range, or I could make a strange peace with it, and walk anyway, and let the needle do what needles do.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I chose the peace. And it was in that peace, a year or two later, that the phone lit up one evening with an inland number and a message that began the last movement of this whole long song — because she was leaving the country, and before she went, after years of the thinnest contact, she wanted, for reasons I did not yet understand, to properly talk.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch9',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Nine',
      title: 'Across the Oceans',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `Life does what life does. It grows you up when you are not looking and it pulls the people you love out to the far edges of the map, and it does all of this without malice, which is somehow the hardest part — there is no one to be angry at, only the great indifferent machinery of time and opportunity, carrying everyone off to their separate futures.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She went to Germany. She had finished her degree, brilliantly, the way she did everything, and won a place at a master's programme in the sciences she had loved since she was the calmest girl in an eleventh-standard classroom, and then a position after it, and just like that the girl at the door became a woman on another continent. She studies the Earth for a living now — remote sensing, she calls it, reading the planet from the sky, mapping lands and waters from satellites for people who need to know where the water is going and where the forests are dying. There is something so exactly _her_ about it that it makes me ache: of course she reads the whole world from a great calm height. Of course she maps the places she cannot walk. She was always doing that, even at sixteen, sitting still at the centre of a room and taking the measure of the whole thing without ever seeming to move.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She chose Europe because she loves to travel, because the whole continent was a doorway to her, a dozen countries a train ride apart, and she was never, ever going to be a woman who sat still in one room. I knew that about her before she knew it about herself. I had watched her want the world from the middle of a classroom in a small coastal city, and now she had gone and taken it, and I was — I want to be honest — I was proud of her in a way that had nothing to do with wanting her, a clean bright uncomplicated pride, the way you are proud of the sea for being large.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I stayed. Here. In Vizag, by the same Bay of Bengal I have breathed my whole life, an engineer in a tower of glass, building things that a great many people use and no one ever sees, the invisible plumbing of other people's convenience. Same city. Same sea. Same salt in the air that was in it the morning she walked through the door.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I used to find that unbearable — that she had crossed the whole world and I had not crossed the road. But I have made a strange peace with it, and part of the peace is this thought, which I have never told anyone: it is the _same sea._ The Bay opens into the Indian Ocean and the Indian Ocean into all the others, one single body of water wearing a dozen names, and the wave that touches my feet on the beach road at evening has, somewhere in its long grey memory, touched every shore there is. She is on one edge of the water and I am on another. But it is one water. I have stood at the tide line on bad nights and taken an absurd, real comfort from that — that the sea at my feet is, in the only sense that finally matters, the sea at hers.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `The message came on an ordinary evening. _Hey Kiaan. It's been forever. I'm moving abroad next month — big change, kind of terrifying honestly. Can we talk properly before I go? Like actually talk. I feel like I owe some people a real goodbye._` },
        { type: 'p', text: `We talked that night for four hours.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I want to set that call down carefully, because it is the closest we have ever come, in ten years, to the thing itself. It was late — late for me, later for the timezone she was half-living in already, her body caught between two clocks. And something in the lateness, or the leaving, or the years, loosened her, and she talked to me the way she had never talked to me, not at sixteen, not ever. Not the calm still-water V who let the room come to her. A realer one, underneath.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She told me she was frightened. That the excitement everyone expected her to feel kept getting undercut by a loneliness she had not budgeted for — the strangeness of building a whole life in a language that was not her mother's, in a city where no one had known her as a child. She told me she already missed her _Amma_ and _Nanna_ so much it frightened her, that she had not understood, until she was about to leave them, how much of herself was simply _theirs_, made of them, and that the thought of watching them grow old through a phone screen from four thousand miles away was the kind of grief you cannot say out loud to the people who are excited for you. She told me about the FOMO, the ache of watching home continue without her on a lit rectangle in her hand — weddings she would miss, festivals, the ordinary Tuesday dinners that turn out, in the end, to have been the whole of a life.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She let me in. That is the plainest way to say it. For four hours, on the edge of leaving everything, she chose me to be honest with, and I listened the way I have been practising listening to her for ten years, and I said the true things back, and for one night the drawer marked _safe_ did not feel like a prison but like a purpose — I was safe, yes, and safe was exactly what she needed at the edge of the unknown, someone who had known her since the door, someone who wanted nothing from her but her okayness.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And at the very end, near two in the morning, when we had talked ourselves empty and there was nothing left but the soft static of a long-distance line, she said the thing I have kept ever since, pressed flat in the old book of me like a flower whose colour has gone but whose shape remains:` },
        { type: 'em', text: `\u201CIt was really nice talking with you, Kiaan.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `That is all. It promised nothing. It was not a confession, not a door opening, not the beginning of anything. It was a woman, at the end of a long honest night, thanking a good friend. But I have kept it, and I will keep it, because for the length of one evening, out of all the people she could have chosen for her real goodbye, she chose me to be honest with, and there are men who have been given far more and treasured it far less.` },
        { type: 'verse', lines: [
          `You read the oceans now from a great calm height;`,
          `I only ever mapped the eighteen inches between our hands.`,
          `You crossed the whole water to go and find the world —`,
          `and the world, for me, was always only wherever you stand.`,
        ] },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `It was Meera who complicated everything, a few weeks after that call, and she did it without meaning to, which is how the largest things are usually done.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Meera and I had stayed loosely in touch over the years — she was that kind of person, the one who keeps the whole old cohort loosely stitched together, remembering birthdays, resurfacing every few months with a message. She called to ask if I had spoken to V before she left, and I said yes, we had had a good long talk, and there was a small pause on the line, and then Meera said a thing that stopped my heart for a full second.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CGood,\u201D she said. \u201CShe was hoping you would. You know, Kiaan —\u201D and then she stopped herself, the way you stop yourself at the edge of someone else's secret, and said instead, lightly, too lightly, \u201Cnever mind. Just — you two. Honestly.\u201D And she laughed, and changed the subject, and would not be drawn back to it however I circled.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `_You two. Honestly._ I lay awake on it for a week. What did Meera know? What was the end of the sentence she had stopped herself from finishing? For ten years I had assumed I was the only keeper of this thing, the sole author of a one-sided book. And here was V's oldest friend, hinting at a chapter I had not known existed, and then closing it again, and leaving me to lie awake in the light of a single unfinished word.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I did not yet know what she knew. That would come later, at the very end, and it would change nothing about my life and everything about how I understood it. But the hint had been dropped, and I carried it with me into the last hard turn of the whole story — the wall, and the choice, and the thing I finally chose not to say.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch10',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Ten',
      title: 'The Distance That Has No Visa',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `I am not a boy anymore. That is the plainest fact of this chapter, and everything in it follows from that fact. The last-bench boy could afford his hopeless love because he did not yet understand the machinery of the world he was born into. The man understands it perfectly, and understanding it is a kind of grief the boy was spared.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Let me say the hard thing plainly, because I have spent enough of this book being gentle with myself. Her people and my people are not the same kind of people, in the way my country still, quietly and ruinously, insists on measuring. Her name carries one history; mine carries another. In the ordinary run of an Indian life, that quiet difference is a wall — not a wall of hatred, usually, nothing so clean as that, but a wall of a thousand small assumptions, of aunties and horoscopes and the settled certainty of two families about what is _done_ and what is _not done_, a wall that has stood for so long that most people never even walk up to it to see whether it is really there. It is there. I know men who have broken themselves against it and men who never tried, and I have never been sure which ones were wiser.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I used to think, in my most romantic and stupid years, that love was the thing that broke walls. I have since learned that walls mostly break _people_, and that the world is full of the quiet wreckage of ones who thought their feeling was strong enough to matter to a machine that does not feel. I did not want to become that wreckage. More to the point — and this is the turn the whole chapter rests on — I did not want _her_ to become it.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Because there was a clock now, ticking under everything, and I could hear it even across the ocean.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Meera let it slip, in another of her calls, half a warning and half a question, watching to see what I would do with it: that V's family had begun, in the careful preliminary way these things begin, to _look_. To make enquiries. To let it be known, in the quiet channels such news travels, that their daughter abroad was of an age, and that suitable proposals would be considered. Nothing was decided. Nothing was even close. But the season had turned, in her life as in mine, toward the third term of my mother's old formula — _marriage_ — and I understood that somewhere in the world, in careful conversations I would never hear, my whole ten-year devotion was being quietly outrun by the ordinary schedule of an ordinary family doing what families do.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I sat with that, for many nights, by the sea. And I came to the hardest decision of the whole story, which was not to act.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Understand what I mean, because it is easy to mistake it for cowardice, and I have examined it long enough to know it is not — or not only.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I could have told her. After ten years, I finally had the courage the boy on the midnight phone call lacked. I could have picked up the phone, on any of those nights, and finally said the three lines that have lived folded in my pocket since I was eighteen. I had earned the right to say them, God knows. I had waited longer than any reasonable person waits for anything.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `But I asked myself a question I had never been mature enough to ask before, and the question was not _what do I want?_ The question was: _what would my saying it do to her?_` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And I saw it clearly, the way you finally see things at twenty-six that were invisible at eighteen. She was standing at the edge of a hard new life, four thousand miles from her Amma and Nanna, frightened, lonely, trying to build something enormous in a language not her own, with a family beginning gently to arrange her future along the only lines they understood. And into all of that, I would drop — what? A ten-year confession she never asked for and cannot use. A love that leads nowhere the world will permit. A beautiful, useless weight, handed to a woman who is already carrying more than she can lift, by a man who calls himself her friend. She would have to _manage_ it. She would have to find something kind to say, and carry the guilt of not being able to say more, and lose, forever, the one uncomplicated thing I had ever given her — the safety of a friend who wanted nothing.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `To confess, I finally understood, would be the most selfish thing I could do dressed as the bravest. It would ease my ten-year ache by transferring it to her. It would let me finally set down my burden by placing it on the shoulders of the person I claim to love most in the world.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `So I chose the silence. Again. But it was a different silence than the boy's on the midnight call — his was made of fear, and mine was made of something I can only call love, the grown kind, the kind that has finally learned the difference between wanting someone and wanting their good. The boy stayed silent to protect himself. The man stayed silent to protect her. It is the same silence from the outside. From the inside it is the difference between a prison and a gift.` },
        { type: 'verse', lines: [
          `I kept the three lines folded, as I have for ten years —`,
          `not now from fear, but because you are carrying enough.`,
          `Let the wall be mine to stand against, and not yours;`,
          `let me love you the one way that costs you nothing, and is enough.`,
        ] },
        { type: 'p', text: `That is where the story would have ended, I thought — in a mature, quiet, permanent silence, a love folded up forever and filed under the kindest possible sacrifice. A man who loved a woman so well that his final act of love was to make sure she never had to know.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `But the story had one more turn in it. Because Meera, who had been circling a secret for months, finally, on a grey evening not long ago, told me the end of her unfinished sentence — and what she told me did not open any door in the world, but it opened every door inside me, and it is the reason this book exists at all.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'ch11',
      kind: 'chapter',
      label: 'Chapter Eleven',
      title: 'What This Love Actually Is',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `People ask me — not in words, they are too polite for words, but with their eyes, with the careful way they change the subject — the same question. _Ten years? For a girl you barely even dated? A girl on another continent who thinks of you as a friend? What is wrong with you?_ It is a fair question. I have asked it of myself on the floor of many nights. And I think I can finally answer it, because Meera gave me the last piece, and with it the whole shape of the thing came clear.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Here is what they do not understand. I did not fall in love with a face at a door. Faces I have gotten over; I am not a monster of fixation, I have loved other faces and let them go. What I fell for — what I have never in ten years been able to get free of — was not a face. It was a _way of being in the world._` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She is calm in a way that makes the room around her quieter. She is kind without wanting credit for it, which is the only kind of kindness that counts. She is mature in a way most of us only perform — she carries some deep, settled, unhurried understanding of life that I have spent ten years trying to learn from her without ever once telling her she was my teacher. She does not chase things. Not brands, not noise, not the frantic scorekeeping the rest of us mistake for living. She wants the world, but she wants it gently, from a great calm height, the way she reads the Earth from the sky. To be near that, even from a corner, even from across an ocean, is to be near a peace I have never found anywhere else, and once you have stood in that particular light you spend the rest of your life a little cold everywhere else.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `You get over a face. You do not get over a _soul_ that felt like home the first second you saw it. That is not obsession. It is recognition. It is the specific, unrepeatable click of a key finding, once in a life, the exact lock it was cut for — and the terrible joke of my particular life is that the lock was on a door I was never going to be allowed to walk through.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `And then, that grey evening, Meera finished her sentence.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `We were on the phone. She had been quiet, and then she said, carefully, as if setting something fragile on a table between us, \u201CKiaan. I'm going to tell you something, and I need you to promise you won't do anything stupid with it. Not call her. Not confess your whole heart. Nothing. She would kill me for telling you, and it doesn't change anything, and you know it doesn't. But I've watched you for ten years and I think you've earned it.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `I said nothing. I could not.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `\u201CShe kept them,\u201D Meera said. \u201CThe birthday messages. Every single one. Ten years of them. She has a folder — an actual folder, on her phone, going back to the first December after school. I saw it once, years ago, by accident, and I asked her about it, and she got that quiet look she gets and she said — \u201D Meera's voice did something \u201C— she said, _he's the only one who has never once forgotten. In ten years. Not once. Do you know what that is, Meera? To be remembered like that by someone who wants nothing from you? It's the safest I've ever felt._ And then she never spoke about it again, and I never asked, and I've carried it around for years not knowing what I was supposed to do with it.\u201D` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `I have tried to describe what that did to me and I keep failing, so let me just tell you the facts of it. I was standing at the window. It was raining, the thin grey rain the coast gets in the turning of the year. And I understood, all at once, that the book I thought I had been writing alone was not, after all, a one-sided thing. That for ten years, on the other side of an ocean, in a folder on a phone, a woman had been quietly keeping every lamp I lit. That she had known. That she had always known. That the wishes I sent into the dark, believing they touched her only for a moment before folding back up, had in fact been landing, and being gathered, and kept — that somewhere in the careful accounting of her guarded heart there was a line that read _he never forgets_, and that she had built, out of my ten Decembers, a small private proof that she was loved safely by someone who asked for nothing.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `It changes nothing. Meera was right about that. The wall is still the wall; the ocean is still the ocean; her family is still, gently, looking; and my three lines are still folded in a pocket where they will, I am now nearly certain, remain until I die. We will almost certainly never be an _us._ The knowing does not move a single stone of the impossible.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `And yet it changed everything, inside, because it turned my ten years from a delusion into a _correspondence._ I had not been shouting into an empty room. I had been writing letters that were received, and read, and kept. She never wrote back the thing I longed for. But she kept every letter. And there is a kind of love — I know this now — that does not need to be returned in order to be real. It only needs, once, to have been _received._` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `So here, at the end, is what this love actually is, the thing it took me ten years and one grey rainy evening to understand.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Somewhere along the way, without my noticing the moment it happened, my love changed its shape. It stopped being a question — _will she be mine, will she ever be mine, how do I make her mine_ — and it became, quietly, a blessing. It stopped asking to _keep_ her and started only asking that she be _well._ Let her be happy, whatever the answer. Let the new country be kind to her. Let the loneliness pass. Let her Amma and Nanna stay well long enough for her to hold them again. Let whatever man her careful family finds be gentle with her, and see her, really see her, the way I saw her from a corner at sixteen. Let her be happy. That is the whole of the prayer now. That is what is left when you burn a love for ten years and let all the wanting cook away — a small hard bright residue that wants the beloved's good more than it wants the beloved.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `That is the only kind of love that can survive a decade without being fed. Not the roaring kind. Not the kind that needs. The kind that blesses. The low blue flame that asks nothing and warms a room no one else can see and keeps, faithfully, a calendar.` },
        { type: 'em', text: `That is why it lasted. That is why it lasts.` },
      ],
    },

    {
      id: 'epilogue',
      kind: 'epilogue',
      label: 'Epilogue',
      title: 'It\u2019s Always Her',
      blocks: [
        { type: 'p', text: `So here I am. Twenty-six. Vizag. Successful enough on paper, wiser than the last-bench boy, mostly at peace — and still carrying, in one corner of my chest, a single unfinished thing that refuses to be renovated, that I have stopped trying to renovate, that I have decided instead to simply let stand, the way you leave one old wall of a house because the whole memory of the place is somehow load-bearing on it.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `It is the twenty-fifth of December again. Of course it is. That is why I finally wrote all this down — the date came round, as it always comes round, and something in me was tired of carrying the whole book unwritten, and I thought: let it be _said_ once, even if the only ones who ever read it are me and the sea and whatever God I remember on this one night of the year.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `The lamp is lit. The little brass lamp from the man on the beach road, filled with oil, burning its small steady flame on my desk while the rest of the city sleeps. In a while I will send the message — the eleventh one, if you count from the first December after school. I already know it will be brief this year. Some years the wish wants to be a paragraph; this year it wants to be a line. _Happy birthday. I hope this year is gentle with you. — always, Kiaan._ And she will read it, tomorrow, in her morning that is my night, four thousand miles and four and a half hours away, and she will add it to the folder, the way she has added the other ten, and neither of us will say the enormous thing that lives under the small one.` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Meera told me one more thing, at the end of that grey evening, and I have saved it for last because it is the only door in this whole book that I have left standing open.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `She said V is thinking of coming home for a while. Not forever — nothing so simple as forever. But the loneliness of the far country has worn at her, and there is talk of a long visit, a season back in the country of her Amma and Nanna, some months in which she might, among other things, come down to the coast, to the old city, to the sea. \u201CShe asked about you,\u201D Meera said, careful as ever. \u201CJust — whether you were still in Vizag. Whether you were happy.\u201D And then, because Meera has known me for ten years and loves me in her sharp unsentimental way: \u201CI don't know what any of it means, Kiaan. Maybe nothing. Probably nothing. But she asked.\u201D` },
        { type: 'p', text: `_But she asked._ I have not built anything on it. I have learned, at last, not to build cathedrals out of single sentences — that was the boy's mistake, and I have buried the boy. I do not think this is a story that ends with the two of us. I have made my peace with the maybe; I made it long ago, and it is a real peace, not a wound wearing a peaceful face.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `But she asked whether I was still here. And I am. I have always been here. Same city, same sea, same salt in the air that was in it the morning she came through the door. If she comes down to the coast this winter, she will find the boy from the last bench grown into a man who never left — standing where he has always stood, at the tide line, at the edge of the one water that touches both our shores, with a lamp that has been lit for her eleven Decembers running, and three lines still folded over his heart that he will, almost certainly, never say.` },
        { type: 'p', text: `Almost certainly. That is the whole of the hope I will allow myself, and it is enough. _Almost._` },
        { type: 'break' },
        { type: 'p', text: `Whoever asks my heart whom it belongs to — the careful relatives, the kind women, the well-meaning friends, my own tired reason at three in the morning — it will not even pause to check its records. It does not consider the evidence. It answers the way water answers gravity, the way the tide answers the moon it will never touch, the way it has answered every single day for ten years and will, I now know, answer for ten more, and the ten after that.` },
        { type: 'em', text: `It\u2019s always her.` },
      ],
    },
  ],
}

